  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Lecce who spends several hours daily on social media, I’ve come to understand that managing fake content requires a blend of practical habits and mindfulness. My parents, both PhDs, taught me the value of critical thinking from a young age, even though I only completed lower secondary school. This foundation helps me approach online information with a cautious but not overly anxious mindset. I find that reading novels has given me a knack for spotting inconsistencies in stories—just like how I look for gaps in online posts. When I see something that feels off, I pause and ask myself: 'Does this align with what I know?' For instance, a recent post about a local Lecce festival that claimed to have been held in 2023 but was actually from 2021 made me pause. I cross-checked with official sources and community groups before sharing. My high conscientiousness helps me stay organized; I’ve created a simple checklist for verifying content: check the source, look for dates, and see if it matches my knowledge. I also rely on the Buddhist principles I’ve learned through my Hindu practice to stay calm—'mindfulness' means not reacting impulsively to false information. While I enjoy cycling and playing video games, these hobbies help me reset my focus and reduce the stress that fake news can cause. It’s important to remember that not all content is harmful, but being selective ensures I stay connected to the truth without letting anxiety take over. My children, who are now adults, often remind me that it’s okay to take breaks from social media when it feels overwhelming. In the end, managing fake content is about balance—using my curiosity to learn, my discipline to act, and my calm to stay grounded.",
